body:
Hi!

I don't remember all the details, but I used a freeze_graph.py script. Something like described in this blog post:

https://blog.metaflow.fr/tensorflow-how-to-freeze-a-model-and-serve-it-with-a-python-api-d4f3596b3adc

The script can be found here:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/python/tools/freeze_graph.py

Thanks for your response Nikita,
unfortunately the script asks for the output list and I'm not sure what needs to be included to be compatible with the PI module. If I include all the variables, it generates a much larger file than the one for the RGB version and the starnet script returns an 'invalid checkpoint' error.
I think output should be "generator/g_deconv7/Sub". Let me know if this will work!

Hi Nikita, almost there. The size and generated structure are really close but I receive an error from PI which is not ease to debug. Does this remind you of anything? Before freezing the model, we have to save it. Is it possible that there was some special settings for this operation so it can be used with the PI script?

![Sans titre](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/68965254/89221679-aef58b80-d5a1-11ea-8aef-9a69e5d2890e.png)

Hm, this is weird, I don't remember having any problems - just froze the graph and used it...

Here is the code I used to do this, maybe this will help somehow:

```
import os
import freeze_graph

checkpoint_state_name = "model.ckpt"
input_graph_name = "starnet.pb"
output_graph_name = "starne_weights.pb"

input_graph_path = os.path.join("./", input_graph_name)
input_saver_def_path = ""
input_binary = False
input_checkpoint_path = os.path.join("./", 'saved_checkpoint')


output_node_names = "generator/g_deconv7/Sub" 
restore_op_name = "save/restore_all" # not used
filename_tensor_name = "save/Const:0" # not used
output_graph_path = os.path.join("./", output_graph_name)
clear_devices = False

freeze_graph.freeze_graph("./starnet_generator.pb",
                          "",
                          True,
                          "./model.ckpt",
                          output_node_names,
                          restore_op_name,
                          filename_tensor_name,
                          "./starnet_generator_weights.pbtxt",
                          clear_devices,
                          "")
```
Doesn't help, same error! Do you have the script that was used to generate the previous step, aka saving the input_graph_name starnet.pb from a checkpoint state?
Yes! I uploaded the script - export.py - try using that!

So based on the actual git repository, the gen_sub list at least one item that is not in the graph:

"AssertionError: generator/g_conv1/LeakyRelu/alpha is not in graph"

Well, it seems to be working on my end - generator/g_conv1/LeakyRelu/alpha is in the model if you look at model.py file

Not sure what is the problem here....

You know what? I can't find any 'generator/g_conv1/LeakyRelu/alpha' in the file on this git. Or is it not found as alpha in the file? :-)

Ok got it tf.nn.leaky_relu(layers[-1], 0.2) alpha=0.2
Try now with the new list!

Really sorry, just another error message on another parameter: 

generator/g_conv1/batch_normalization/FusedBatchNorm

Ok, let's take a step back here. I uploaded all the necessary files. I just cloned the repo and everything works as expected.

Please try to clone the repo, download my weights from Dropbox, and run
```
python starnet.py export
python freeze.py
```

Everything should work!

I have re-installed python environment so that I use the same config that was mentioned in the read.me file. Python 3.6.3, tensorflow-gpu (1.4.0). I was previously using TF 1.15 and noticed that some tensor names had changed. I'm still facing not found tensor names in the graph (example : generator/g_conv1/batch_normalization/AssignMovingAvg/sub/x) . How did you generate the gen_sub.txt ? Does it come from the starnet.pbtxt file?

I finally managed to adequately generate the file by extracting all the nodes from the generators layer with the following line in the export.py file.

gen_layers = [n.name for n in tf.get_default_graph().as_graph_def().node if n.name.find("generator") == 0]

thanks for your help!
Let me know if you were able to generate a working checkpoint file for PI!

Will certainly do when completed. Why does your model differ from the proposed PAN one? Some relu are not performed in some generator's layers (ex. g_conv8). In the paper they added a relu rectifier at the end.

Not sure what PAN is? Overall, I tried to combine approaches from different papers and tried to find combination that works better, in contrast to just using some particular one that was published. Also, I don't have g_conv8 in the model, lol, and what do you mean "Some relu are not performed in some generator's layers"? All of them have ReLUs!

Ok thanks for your comments. I was refering to table II of this paper https://arxiv.org/pdf/1706.09138.pdf 

regards
I see. I had a very crappy GPU with little memory, so I used lower resolution of input (256 vs 512) so I dropped one layer of convolutions!
